  "text": "## Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling Across Go Services\n\n### kubernetes/kubernetes\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go` implements `SetupSignalContext()` and `SetupSignalHandler()` functions that register for SIGTERM and SIGINT signals\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal_posix.go` defines `shutdownSignals = []os.Signal{os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM}`\n- The signal handlers use `signal.Notify()` to register with a buffered channel (capacity 2) to capture up to two signals\n- A context is created with `context.WithCancel()` that gets cancelled on the first signal\n- On the second signal, the program exits immediately with `os.Exit(1)`, allowing forceful termination if graceful shutdown hangs\n\n**Graceful Shutdown Pattern:**\n- The implementation uses context cancellation as the shutdown mechanism\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/kms/internal/plugins/_mock/plugin.go` demonstrates the pattern with `withShutdownSignal()` that wraps context and returns a cancellable context\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/kms/pkg/service/grpc_service.go` calls `GracefulStop()` on the gRPC server when context is done\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- When shutdown signal is received, context is cancelled which triggers cleanup in dependent services\n- The two-signal approach ensures: first signal initiates graceful shutdown, second signal forces immediate exit\n\n### grafana/grafana\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/commands/cli.go` implements `listenToSystemSignals()` that registers for SIGTERM, SIGINT (via os.Interrupt), and SIGHUP signals\n- Uses separate channels for SIGHUP and SIGTERM/SIGINT to handle reload separately from shutdown\n- Signal handlers run in an infinite loop checking both signal channels\n\n**Graceful Shutdown Pattern:**\n- On SIGTERM/SIGINT, creates a context with 30-second timeout: `context.WithTimeout(ctx, 30*time.Second)`\n- Calls `s.Shutdown(ctx, ...)` with the timeout context\n- `pkg/server/server.go` Shutdown method:\n  - Uses `sync.Once` to ensure shutdown only happens once\n  - Calls `managerAdapter.Shutdown()` to shutdown background services\n  - Waits on context with a select statement\n- `pkg/services/grpcserver/service.go` shutdown method:\n  - Calls `s.server.GracefulStop()` in a goroutine\n  - Has explicit timeout handling with `time.After(s.cfg.GracefulShutdownTimeout)`\n  - If graceful stop completes in time, logs success; if timeout occurs, calls `Stop()` to force shutdown\n  - Configuration timeout is defined in `pkg/setting/setting_grpc.go` with default 10 seconds\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- gRPC server drains connections first via `GracefulStop()` before forcing stop\n- Background services shut down before gRPC server\n- 30-second overall shutdown timeout ensures bounded shutdown time\n\n**Multiple Signal Handlers:**\n- Operators in `pkg/operators/provisioning/` and `pkg/operators/iam/` each register their own signal handlers\n- Each creates a context and cancels it on SIGTERM/SIGINT signal\n\n### prometheus/prometheus\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- `cmd/prometheus/main.go` uses `oklog/run` library for service orchestration\n- Creates a channel `term := make(chan os.Signal, 1)` and registers: `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)`\n- Signal is received via the run group's executor pattern\n\n**Graceful Shutdown Pattern:**\n- Uses `oklog/run` Group to manage multiple services with coordinated shutdown\n- When SIGTERM/SIGINT is received, the signal triggers the group's interrupt function which calls Stop() on all services\n- Services are stopped in reverse order of registration\n\n**Drain on Shutdown:**\n- `notifier/manager.go` defines `Options` struct with `DrainOnShutdown bool` field\n- `notifier/sendloop.go` implements the drain pattern:\n  - `stop()` method checks if `DrainOnShutdown` is true\n  - If true, calls `drainQueue()` which processes all pending alerts before returning\n  - If false, logs warning and counts dropped alerts\n  - `drainQueue()` loops through queue calling `sendOneBatch()` until queue is empty\n- Configuration flag `--alertmanager.drain-notification-queue-on-shutdown` (default true) controls this behavior\n- `notifier/manager.go` Run method returns only after all pending notifications are drained\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- Discovery managers stop first (notification and scrape)\n- Notifier manager stops with queue draining\n- Rule manager stops\n- Web handler stops\n- Each service's Stop() function is called in reverse order, allowing earlier services to drain while later services are still active\n\n### Common Patterns\n\n1. **Signal Registration:** All three use `os/signal.Notify()` with buffered channels\n2. **Multi-Signal Handling:** Support for second signal to force exit (Kubernetes explicitly, others via framework)\n3. **Graceful Shutdown Mechanism:** \n   - Kubernetes: Context cancellation\n   - Grafana: Explicit shutdown methods with timeout context\n   - Prometheus: Service group orchestration with drain functionality\n4. **Timeout Protection:** Bounded shutdown time prevents indefinite hangs\n   - Kubernetes: Second signal forces exit\n   - Grafana: Explicit 30-second timeout (or service-specific like 10s for gRPC)\n   - Prometheus: Service dependencies ensure cleanup completes or forces stop\n5. **Drain Before Stop:** Important for notification/alert systems to avoid losing data\n"
